        <h2>Use of Resources</h2>
        <h3>Nativism in the 1920’s</h3>
        <p>Text Excerpts:  <i>“This fellow has worked out the whole thing. It’s up to us, who are the dominant race, to watch out or these other races will have control of things.”</i></p>
        <p>Explanation of relation to history:
The predominant idea of “white supremacy” was threatened by recent activity giving other races the right to vote and the enlightening image of African Americans. During this time, the Jazz Age was rising to popularity, bringing fame and recognition to African Americans such as Louis Armstrong. Some individuals, such as Tom Buchanan, felt that this occasion is “threatening” to civilization.</p>
        <p>Young WWI veterans had a new outlook on life: to live on the edge and appreciate the spoils of life. The predominant idea of “white supremacy” was threatened by recent activity giving other races the right to vote. Native Americans were given the right to vote in 1924 by the BIA, Bureau of Indian Affairs. Following the new law, Virginia made racially-targeted laws to limit the new freedoms of Native Americans. Virginia’s Racial Integrity Act of 1924.</p>
        <p>Source Citation - </br>"American Experience | Monkey Trial | People & Events - PBS." 2002. 20 Feb. 2015 &lt;http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/monkeytrial/peopleevents/e_jazzage.html&gt;</p>
